[[/SECTION]]

[[SECTION]]
TITLE: Software Architecture Specification

[TEXT]
STATEMENT: >>>
This section constitutes the Software Architecture Specification (SAS) as
required by EN 50716:2023, Clause 7.3 and Table A.1 (document 9). The SAS
defines the top-level structure of the software, the allocation of requirements
to components, the data and control flows, and the architectural techniques
applied to achieve the required safety integrity level.

The SAS is the primary input to the Software Design Specification (section 3)
and to the Software Interface Specifications (section 4).
<<<

[[SECTION]]
TITLE: Architectural overview and decomposition

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: SAD-010
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Architecture overview and partitioning
STATEMENT: >>>
The software shall be structured as a <layered / component-based /
partition-based> architecture comprising the following top-level partitions:

  Partition                  | SIL   | Responsibility
  ---------------------------|-------|------------------------------------------
  <Safety kernel>            | SIL n | <Core safety logic, output commands>
  <Application layer>        | SIL n | <Function-specific application logic>
  <HW abstraction layer>     | SIL n | <Device drivers, BSP>
  <Diagnostics & monitoring> | SIL n | <Built-in self-test, health monitoring>
  <Non-safety services>      | SIL 0 | <Logging, HMI, maintenance interface>

Freedom from interference between SIL partitions and between safety and
non-safety partitions shall be demonstrated by analysis or test. The analysis
method is described in: <document ID or section reference>.

Architecture diagram reference: <figure number or attached diagram>
<<<
BASIC: R
SIL_1: HR
SIL_2: HR
SIL_3: HR
SIL_4: HR
VERIFICATION_METHOD: Inspection, Review
RATIONALE: EN 50716:2023, Clause 7.3 and Table A.1, doc 9 – Software Architecture Specification.

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: SAD-011
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Architectural decomposition into modules
STATEMENT: >>>
The software architecture shall be decomposed into a defined set of modules.
Each module shall have:
  a) A unique name and identifier.
  b) A single, well-defined responsibility (single-responsibility principle).
  c) Clearly specified inputs, outputs, and dependencies.
  d) An assigned SIL classification consistent with the functions it implements.

Module decomposition:

  Module ID | Module name              | SIL   | Depends on
  ----------|--------------------------|-------|------------------
  <MOD-01>  | <Safety kernel>          | SIL n | <MOD-03, MOD-04>
  <MOD-02>  | <Application logic>      | SIL n | <MOD-01>
  <MOD-03>  | <HW abstraction>         | SIL n | <none>
  <MOD-04>  | <Communication stack>    | SIL n | <MOD-03>
  <MOD-05>  | <Diagnostics>            | SIL n | <MOD-03>
  <MOD-06>  | <Non-safety services>    | SIL 0 | <MOD-03>

Coupling between modules shall be minimised and restricted to well-defined
interfaces (see section 4). No direct access to the internal state of another
module is permitted. Cohesion within each module shall be maximised.
<<<
BASIC: R
SIL_1: HR
SIL_2: HR
SIL_3: HR
SIL_4: HR
VERIFICATION_METHOD: Inspection, Review
RATIONALE: EN 50716:2023, Clause 7.3 and Table A.1, doc 9 – Software Architecture Specification.

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: SAD-012
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Structured methodology for architecture design
STATEMENT: >>>
The software architecture shall be derived from the SRS using a defined
structured methodology that ensures systematic coverage of all requirements.

Methodology applied: <e.g. SADT / IDEF0 / UML / EAST-ADL / SA-SD>
Reference document:  <methodology guide or standard>

The methodology shall provide:
  a) A top-down, systematic derivation of the software structure from the
     SRS functional and interface requirements.
  b) Documented design decisions with rationale, including rejected
     alternatives and their justification.
  c) Traceability from each architectural element to the SRS requirement(s)
     it satisfies.
  d) A defined architecture review checkpoint (see SAD-090) before detailed
     design commences.
<<<
