[[/SECTION]]

[[SECTION]]
TITLE: Error handling and fault tolerance

[TEXT]
STATEMENT: >>>
The following requirements specify the fault-tolerance and error-handling
techniques to be applied in the software architecture, per EN 50716:2023,
Table A.3. The techniques are selected and applied according to the target SIL.
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: SAD-030
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Defensive programming
STATEMENT: >>>
Defensive programming techniques shall be applied at all module boundaries
and at all external interfaces (SRS-030 to SRS-032). The following measures
shall be implemented:

  a) Input validation: all inputs received from external sources, other modules,
     or hardware shall be range-checked and plausibility-checked before use.
  b) Return-value checking: return values and error codes from all function
     and API calls shall be checked; unexpected values shall be handled.
  c) No assumption about caller behaviour: each module shall enforce its own
     preconditions rather than relying on callers to guarantee them.
  d) Initialisation: all variables, buffers, and data structures shall be
     explicitly initialised to a defined safe value before use.
  e) Safe defaults: in the absence of valid input, the module shall adopt
     the defined safe state (SRS-020 series, fail-safe behaviour field).
<<<
BASIC: --
SIL_1: HR
SIL_2: HR
SIL_3: HR
SIL_4: HR
VERIFICATION_METHOD: Inspection, Review
RATIONALE: EN 50716:2023, Table A.3 – Defensive programming.

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: SAD-031
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Fault detection and diagnosis
STATEMENT: >>>
The software architecture shall incorporate mechanisms for detecting and
diagnosing faults at runtime. The following shall be specified and implemented:

  a) Built-in self-test (BIST): a self-test sequence shall be executed at
     startup and, where feasible, periodically during operation. The BIST
     shall cover: RAM check, ROM/flash CRC check, CPU register check, and
     <project-specific checks>.
  b) Runtime monitoring: the safety kernel shall monitor the execution time
     and sequence of safety-critical tasks; deviations shall trigger a
     safe-state transition.
  c) Diagnostic coverage objective: <state the target DC, e.g. ≥ 90 % for
     SIL 3; the diagnostic coverage shall be estimated during design and
     confirmed by analysis>.
  d) Fault logging: detected faults shall be logged to non-volatile storage
     with a timestamp, fault code, and context data.

Diagnostic architecture reference: <module / document section>
<<<
BASIC: --
SIL_1: R
SIL_2: R
SIL_3: HR
SIL_4: HR
VERIFICATION_METHOD: Inspection, Analysis
RATIONALE: EN 50716:2023, Table A.3 – Fault detection and diagnosis.

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: SAD-032
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Error detecting codes
STATEMENT: >>>
Error detecting codes shall be applied to protect safety-critical data
from corruption due to hardware faults, memory errors, or communication
errors. The following shall be specified:

  a) Memory integrity: CRC-<n> or equivalent shall be applied to ROM/flash
     code and data images; checked at startup (BIST) and cyclically during
     operation at interval < <n> ms.
  b) RAM integrity: a defined pattern (e.g. walk-bit test or checkerboard)
     shall be applied to safety-critical RAM areas; interval < <n> ms.
  c) Communication data integrity: all safety-critical messages exchanged
     via external interfaces (SRS-032) shall carry a CRC or safety code
     defined by the applicable communication protocol.
  d) Inter-module data integrity: where safety-critical data is passed via
     shared memory between modules, an integrity check (CRC or inverted copy)
     shall be applied.

Error detecting code specifications: <document / section reference>
<<<
BASIC: --
SIL_1: R
SIL_2: R
SIL_3: HR
SIL_4: HR
VERIFICATION_METHOD: Inspection, Testing
RATIONALE: EN 50716:2023, Table A.3 – Error detecting codes.

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: SAD-033
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Failure assertion programming
STATEMENT: >>>
Assertion-based programming shall be used throughout the safety-critical
software to document and enforce invariants. Assertions shall be:

  a) Placed at the preconditions and postconditions of all safety-critical
     functions (pre/post assertions).
  b) Placed at key state transitions to verify that the system state is
     consistent with expectations (state invariant assertions).
  c) Always active in safety-critical code (assertions shall NOT be compiled
     out in release builds).
  d) Implemented so that assertion failure triggers an immediate safe-state
     transition via the defined error-handling path, not an uncontrolled
     exception.

Assertion macro / library: <e.g. SAFETY_ASSERT(condition, fault_code)>
Safe-state handler: <module name / function name>
<<<
BASIC: --
SIL_1: R
SIL_2: R
SIL_3: HR
SIL_4: HR
VERIFICATION_METHOD: Inspection, Review
RATIONALE: EN 50716:2023, Table A.3 – Failure assertion programming.

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: SAD-034
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Diverse programming
STATEMENT: >>>
Where software diversity is required to achieve the target SIL or to
satisfy the hazard analysis (SRS-011), independently developed diverse
software channels shall be specified. Diversity shall be achieved by:

  a) Independent development teams with no shared design artefacts between
     channels at the detailed design level.
  b) Use of different algorithms or design approaches for each channel.
  c) Use of different compilers or tool chains for each channel, or
     cross-compilation with diverse verification.
  d) Independent test teams verifying each channel.

Diversity scope for this project: <describe which functions use diverse
channels, or state "Not applied – diversity not required at this SIL level">

If not applied: state the justification and confirm this is consistent with
the hazard analysis and applicable national technical rules.
<<<
