[[SECTION]]
TITLE: Design principles and constraints

[TEXT]
STATEMENT: >>>
The following requirements specify the design and implementation principles
to be applied throughout the architecture and detailed design phases, per
EN 50716:2023, Table A.4.
<<<

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: SAD-040
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Modular approach
STATEMENT: >>>
The software shall be designed and implemented using a modular approach.
The following constraints apply to all safety-related modules:

  a) Maximum module size: < <n> lines of source code (executable statements);
     modules exceeding this limit shall be decomposed.
  b) Each module shall implement a single, clearly identified function or
     abstraction (single-responsibility principle).
  c) Module interfaces shall be the only communication path between modules;
     use of global variables shared between modules is prohibited unless
     explicitly justified and documented.
  d) The module hierarchy shall not exceed <n> levels of nesting.
  e) Each module shall have a dedicated module test specification entry,
     enabling it to be tested independently of other modules.

The module decomposition defined in SAD-011 shall be maintained throughout
detailed design. Any restructuring of modules shall be subject to the
architectural change control process (SP-061).
<<<
BASIC: HR
SIL_1: M
SIL_2: M
SIL_3: M
SIL_4: M
VERIFICATION_METHOD: Inspection
RATIONALE: EN 50716:2023, Table A.4 – Modular approach.

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: SAD-041
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Design and coding standards
STATEMENT: >>>
A defined design standard and coding standard shall be applied throughout
the architecture, design, and implementation phases.

  Design standard: <e.g. project-specific design rule document, reference>
  Coding standard: <e.g. MISRA C:2012, CERT C, or project-specific standard>

Compliance requirements:
  a) All safety-related design artefacts shall conform to the design standard.
     Deviations shall be documented, justified, and approved by the Software
     Verifier before the affected design is baselined.
  b) All safety-related source code shall comply with the coding standard.
     Compliance shall be verified by automated static analysis (<tool name>)
     and by code review (SP-072, SP-021).
  c) Coding standard deviations shall be recorded in the deviation register
     (<document ID or tool reference>) with justification and approval.
  d) The coding standard shall prohibit, at minimum: dynamic memory allocation
     after initialisation, unbounded recursion, use of goto / setjmp / longjmp,
     and reliance on undefined or implementation-defined language behaviour.
<<<
BASIC: HR
SIL_1: HR
SIL_2: HR
SIL_3: M
SIL_4: M
VERIFICATION_METHOD: Inspection, Analysis
RATIONALE: EN 50716:2023, Table A.4 – Design and coding standards.

[REQUIREMENT]
UID: SAD-042
STATUS: Draft
TITLE: Structured programming
STATEMENT: >>>
All safety-related software shall be implemented using structured programming
techniques. The following rules shall be enforced:

  a) Single-entry, single-exit for all functions and control structures.
  b) Only defined structured control constructs shall be used: sequence,
     selection (if/else, switch/case), iteration (for, while, do-while).
  c) The following constructs are prohibited in safety-critical code:
       - goto (unconditional branch)
       - setjmp / longjmp
       - Multiple return points within a function (except via unified exit)
       - Recursion (direct or indirect) unless bounded depth can be proven
         and stack usage is statically determined
  d) Nesting depth of control structures shall not exceed <n> levels; deeper
     nesting shall be refactored into sub-functions.

Compliance shall be verified by static analysis and code inspection (SAD-041).
<<<
